<exercises component="proteus" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="proteus-5-3">
<title>PROTEUS exercises (for Section 5.3)</title>
<introduction>
    <p>
        Each of the following expressions is the result of the Chain Rule being applied to a composite function. In other words, it is the right-hand side of the Chain Rule:
        <me>
            \dfrac{d}{dx} \left[ F(g(x)) \right] = f(g(x)) g'(x)
        </me>. 
        Drag the blocks in each problem below to identify the functions <m>f</m>, <m>g</m>, and <m>g'</m>, and then calculate the original composite function.
    </p>
</introduction>
<exercise xml:id="proteus-5-3-draggable-1" label="proteus-5-3-draggable-1">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <me>
                2 (2x+5)^7 = f(g(x)) g'(x)
            </me>
            Drag <m>f(x)</m>, <m>g(x)</m>, <m>g'(x)</m>, and <m>F(g(x))</m> into the box below, in that order.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <blocks layout="horizontal" randomize="yes">
        <block>
            <m>x^7</m>
        </block>
        <block>
            <m>2x+5</m>
        </block>
        <block>
            <m>2</m>
        </block>
        <block>
            <m>\frac{1}{8}(2x+5)^8</m>
        </block>
    </blocks>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="proteus-5-3-draggable-2" label="proteus-5-3-draggable-2">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <me>
                \sin\left(e^x\right) e^x = f (g(x) ) g'(x)
            </me>
            Drag <m>f(x)</m>, <m>g(x)</m>, <m>g'(x)</m>, and <m>F(g(x))</m> into the box below, in that order.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <blocks layout="horizontal" randomize="yes">
        <block>
            <m>\sin(x)</m>
        </block>
        <block>
            <m>e^x</m>
        </block>
        <block>
            <m>e^x</m>
        </block>
        <block>
            <m>-\cos\left(e^x\right)</m>
        </block>
    </blocks>
</exercise>
